commit.message:
Don't use 'final' specifier in a 'final class'

It's redundant.

Use '=default' for operator==

Remove workaround for gcc-10 bug.

Use transparent comparator in std::map

Replace
    std::map<K, V>      // 3rd template parameter defaults to std::less<K>
with
    std::map<K, V, std::less<>>

See here for why the latter is 'better':
    https://stackoverflow.com/questions/20317413/what-are-transparent-comparators

For example with:
    std::map<std::string, int> myMap;
    ...
    myMap.find("abc");
The find() method would internally construct a std::string object from
the string literal (const char*) "abc". If we instead define the map as:
    std::map<std::string, int, std::less<>> myMap;
then the find() method can directly compare std::string objects with
string-literals. In other words: it can perform heterogeneous
comparisons.

It's unfortunate that heterogeneous comparisons can't be done with the
shorter syntax. See the above stackoverflow post for the reasoning (in
short: backwards compatibility between c++11 and c++14).

--

This patch changes all std::map's in openMSX so that heterogeneous
comparisons can be used. Though at first sight I couldn't see any
opportunities where this could be exploited. But it's good to be
prepared anyway.

Removed unused (local) variable / parameter

Suggested by 'sonarcloud".

Midi_w32.cc: fix misuse of strncpy

Not a problem in practice because the string we're copying ("midi-out")
is for sure smaller than the destination buffer.
combine-dmk.cc: added missing fclose() call

Switch from 'l' to 'L' literal suffix

And:
 ll  -> LL
 ul  -> UL
 ull -> ULL

My preference was always for the lower case version. But 'sonarcloud'
suggested to change it. The rationale is that the digit '1' and the
lower case 'l' look very similar (of course depending on the exact font
you're using). And then this might get confusing for literals like
'10l'. That argument convinced me. Hence this patch

commit.message:
Prefer std::array over plain-C arrays

The former more easily integrates in c++ and can be passed by value
(does't decay to a pointer) etc.

In many cases the difference doesn't matter, but it's good to be
consistent.

We already followed this rule in most of the code. This patch also fixes
it in some windows specific code (which I can't easily test myself).
Though if I made a mistake it will manifest itself as a compile error
(not a bug at runtime) and then the github build action will inform me.
Contrib/openmsx-control-stdio.cc: tweaks
Contrib/dmk: factor out common code between the different dmk* utilities
Fix block sizes of several ROM types.

Remove 'inline' from function declarations (not from definitions)

The stuff below applies only to member functions. Instead for free
functions, defined in header files, there is no choice, those must
always be marked 'inline'.

'sonarcloud' suggests to remove 'inline' from function declaraction and
instead put it on the function definition. Rationale:
* The function declaration is meant as documention for (human) callers
  of the code. Functionally it doesn't matter whether the function gets
  inlined or not.
* Inlining is an implementation strategy, so it belong together with the
  implementation of the function (so on the definition). And technically
  (for the compiler) for inlining to be possible the declaration must
  anyway be visible for the caller.
I can see the appeal of this reasoning.

In our code, even before this patch, we actually have relatively few
functions marked as inline. There were 2 main exceptions:
* Many of the sound-device emulation code.
* And the (V9990,VDP)CmdEngine code.
These mark many (private) methods 'inline'. In the past this was a hint
to the compiler to inline those methods. Though modern compilers more
and more ignore such hints. In most of our code we don't bother anymore
with such hints.

So instead of moving 'inline' from the declaration to the definition
this patch also removes a lot of 'inline' annotations.

Set block size to 0 for non-mapper ROMs

Triggered by this PR:
  https://github.com/openMSX/openMSX/pull/1600

Thanks to pvmm for pointing out the problem and proposing a solution.
Thanks to MBilderbeek for suggesting an alternative solution.
I merely verified the idea and pushed it.

Background info:
Our `RomPlain` and `RomPageNN` classes currently inherit from
`Rom8kBBlocks`. That should be only an implementation detail (it allowed
to reused some of the debugging infrastructure) because these mappers
can't actually be switched.

Unfortunately this implementation detail did leak out. Till yesterday I
thought it leaked because we inherited from `Rom8kBBlocks` and that then
announces a 8kB block size. But I was mistaken, and MBilderbeek pointed
out this info is (independently from the class hierarchy) stored in
`romTypeInfoArray` in `RomInfo.cc`.

So all this patch does is correct the info in that table.

combine-dmk: modernize based on on suggestions from sonarcloud and clang-tidy

Fix crash on loading layout, after 93e82a566b5

In commit 93e82a566b5 we postponed removing elements from the 'parts'
vector, to avoid iterating over a changing vector.

Though now the problem is that (in one specific loop) we now visit
objects that are already deleted.

Now I changed the code to:
* In unregisterPart() replace the to be remove part with nullptr. This
  avoids the problem of iterating over a changing vector (the content of
  the vector changes (that's fine), but the vector does not grow or
  shrink).
* In some loops we now check that an element has been replaced by
  nullptr before using it.
* In updateParts() we remove all nullptrs from the vector.

This fixes the bug, and it's also a bit more efficient.

Fix compile error in Apple specific code

Apparently std::bit_cast on a variable length array doesn't work? See
patch for details. Reverted to reinterpret_cast.

Replace redundant type with 'auto'

E.g. when the same type is specified twice in the same line:
    VDP* vdp = dynamic_cast<VDP*>(device);
->
    auto* vdp = dynamic_cast<VDP*>(device);

Our code already was quite good in following this rule. But for some
reason I didn't do this for types that were only 3 or 4 chars long (so
stuff like 'int', 'char', 'VDP', ...). Yes, for those types, replacing
the duplicate type with 'auto' makes the line 1 character longer. But
that's not a good reason to introduce an inconsistency.
